2026-04-16 12:36:39 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Load Protection Diode'] hypothesis_explanation="The persistent voltage drop across the load module (specifically, from the anode to the cathode of the protection diode) indicates that while the upstream circuit delivers 0.3592 V to the diode's anode, the voltage at the cathode (and thus at both lamps) is near zero. This strongly suggests that the protection diode in the load module is either open or has developed a high forward resistance, preventing current flow to the lamps and causing the lamps to fail to light whenever the relay tries to switch them on. The result is a periodic lamp-off behavior whenever the circuit attempts to energize the load, while upstream voltages remain as expected. All cable and rail connections exhibit proper continuity and low resistance; thus, the diode is the most likely single point failure."
